{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523940"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:00:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:00:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13934"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13934"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.55,0.24,0.1,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6560"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108299"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6560"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13934"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90702"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"2383"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"10977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13238"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18395"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18489"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40372"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43453"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108299"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of blurred vision and burning sensation in her left eye. She has a medical history of pulmonary sarcoidosis diagnosed three years ago and takes oral prednisone. She does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her visual acuity is 6/6 in the right eye and 6/9 in the left eye. The left eye shows no obvious redness or discharge. There is thickening at the lower eyelid with adhesion to the underlying conjunctiva.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Visual field testing","Slit lamp examination","Fundoscopic examination","Optical coherence tomography","Swinging flashlight test"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms suggestive of symblepharon, a condition where adhesions form between the palpebral (eyelid) and bulbar (eyeball) conjunctiva. Given her history of sarcoidosis, which can cause inflammatory eye complications, careful evaluation of the anterior segment is essential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESlit lamp examination\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial investigation. It allows for magnified, detailed visualisation of the anterior segment, including the conjunctiva, cornea, and eyelids. This enables the clinician to directly assess the presence, location, and extent of conjunctival adhesions characteristic of symblepharon. Fluorescein staining can also be used in conjunction with slit lamp examination to help visualise the extent of conjunctival adhesions and detect any associated epithelial defects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwinging flashlight test\u003C/strong\u003E is used to detect relative afferent pupillary defects, which would be more relevant in conditions affecting the optic nerve or retina. It would not help evaluate conjunctival adhesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOptical coherence tomography\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily used to evaluate retinal and optic nerve pathology. While useful in some cases of posterior segment sarcoidosis involvement, it would not be helpful for assessing anterior segment adhesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFundoscopic examination\u003C/strong\u003E allows assessment of the retina and optic nerve but would not assist in evaluating anterior segment pathology such as symblepharon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVisual field testing\u003C/strong\u003E assesses peripheral vision and is typically used for conditions affecting the optic nerve or visual pathways. It would not provide useful information about conjunctival adhesions or anterior segment inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Symblepharon is a known complication of sarcoidosis, causing adhesions between the palpebral and bulbar conjunctiva.","Sarcoidosis can cause various anterior segment complications including uveitis and conjunctival granulomas.","Slit lamp examination with fluorescein staining are the first-line investigation for suspected symblepharon to assess conjunctival adhesions and epithelial defects."],"references":["Jeffrey R, Dobes J, Chen F. Eye Injuries: Understanding ocular trauma. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2022:51(7). Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2022/july/eye-injuries","Chong K, Fowler B, Bunya V, Dryden S et al. Symblepharon. In: EyeWiki American Academy of Opthalmology [online]. 2024. Available at: https://eyewiki.org/Symblepharon"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90702"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13934"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90702"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-09T14:52:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-09T14:53:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6560"}},"c